title: For Sale/Trade:  1944 Tula made M38 Mosin Nagant
postcontent: Please read the full ad before responding. This is an M38 Mosin nagant chambered in 7.62x54R W/ all matching serials. The rifle works flawlessly and the bore is clean with strong rifling all the way through. Since owning it I have made a point to run amonia/boiling down the barrel and over all the parts after shooting ANY ammo. In short, it is an old work horse that has been well maintained. The furniture was pretty beat up when I got it and some idiot or kindergardener had scratched their initials into the side of the stock. So, I popped it off and refinished it with a dark stain and some outdoor polyurethane. Of course I'm biased but I think it looks way better than the original lacquer.       The days of 75 dollar Mosins are gone and although I am sad to part with this one I shoot it so infrequently that it seems to be time for something else. 91/30s seem to be starting at 200 dollars these days (if you get lucky) and go far higher depending on the particular make. These arent the rarest but they are certainly not common either. This one is a Tula M38 carbine manufactured in 1944 at Tula arsenal, USSR. My understanding is that the m38 is very similar if not identical to the M44 but, being that it was manufactured for troops somewhat removed from the front lines (artillery, supply etc),the foldout bayonet was removed.              For this one I am asking 400 dollars cash. But that said, cash is always in shorter supply so I am willing to trade at a higher value.        If you have something fun, please dont hesitate to make an offer. I dont bite and I will most certainly not be a dick about it if I do not accept! Just no obvious lowball offers. I am not under any pressure to get rid of this and it just wastes the time of everyone involved.

title: For Sale:  CZ 527 CARBINE
postcontent: The Carbine is an intermediate range ‘brush gun.’ Weighing in at less than 6 lbs, this handy rifle has a straight comb walnut stock and open sights. For a long time this was our only model chambered in 7.62×39 (now joined by the 527 Youth Carbine), it combines low recoil with effectiveness on medium-sized game such as deer and wild boar, making it ideal for younger shooters. Both chamberings offered in the Carbine are economical to shoot given their service rifle heritage and the availability of surplus ammunition. Built to CIP specifications, our 7.62×39 chambers are ideal for shooting steel-cased surplus ammo. Designed to shoot .311 bullets, some American brass ammo may not perform as well as the imported steel-cased variety because of SAAMI brass dimensions and varying bullet diameters. Our .223s will happily eat 5.56, since CIP doesn’t differentiate between the two cartridges and just has the higher pressure as its standard. So our .223s will shoot everything from the cheapest Russian steel to match .223 brass ammo.LOG:49839
